In probability theory and statistics, the F&quot;-distributionor F&quot;-ratio, also known as Snedecor&#x27;s &quot;F&quot; distribution or the Fisher–Snedecor distribution (after Ronald Fisher and George W. Snedecor), is a continuous probability distribution that arises frequently as the null distribution of a test statistic, most notably in the analysis of variance (ANOVA) and other &quot;F&quot;-tests.

==Definitions==
The &quot;F&quot;-distribution with &quot;d&quot;1 and &quot;d&quot;2 degrees of freedom is the distribution of

: formula_9

where formula_10 and formula_11 are independent random variables with chi-square distributions with respective degrees of freedom formula_12 and formula_13.

It can be shown to follow that the probability density function (pdf) for &quot;X&quot; is given by

: formula_14

for real &quot;x&quot; &gt; 0. Here formula_15 is the beta function. In many applications, the parameters &quot;d&quot;1 and &quot;d&quot;2 are positive integers, but the distribution is well-defined for positive real values of these parameters.

The cumulative distribution function is

:formula_16

where &quot;I&quot; is the regularized incomplete beta function.

==Properties==
The expectation, variance, and other details about the F(&quot;d&quot;1, &quot;d&quot;2) are given in the sidebox; for &quot;d&quot;2 &gt; 8, the excess kurtosis is

:formula_17

The &quot;k&quot;-th moment of an F(&quot;d&quot;1, &quot;d&quot;2) distribution exists and is finite only when 2&quot;k&quot; &lt; &quot;d&quot;2 and it is equal to

:formula_18

The &quot;F&quot;-distribution is a particular parametrization of the beta prime distribution, which is also called the beta distribution of the second kind.

The characteristic function is listed incorrectly in many standard references (e.g.,). The correct expression is

:formula_19

where &quot;U&quot;(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;z&quot;) is the confluent hypergeometric function of the second kind.

==Related distributions==
===Relation to the chi-squared distribution===
In instances where the &quot;F&quot;-distribution is used, for example in the analysis of variance, independence of formula_20 and formula_21 (defined above) might be demonstrated by applying Cochran&#x27;s theorem.

Equivalently, since the chi-squared distribution is the sum of squares of independent standard normal random variables, the random variable of the &quot;F&quot;-distribution may also be written

:formula_22

where formula_23 and formula_24, formula_25 is the sum of squares of formula_26 random variables from normal distribution formula_27 and formula_28 is the sum of squares of formula_29 random variables from normal distribution formula_30.

In a frequentist context, a scaled &quot;F&quot;-distribution therefore gives the probability formula_31, with the &quot;F&quot;-distribution itself, without any scaling, applying where formula_32 is being taken equal to formula_33. This is the context in which the &quot;F&quot;-distribution most generally appears in &quot;F&quot;-tests: where the null hypothesis is that two independent normal variances are equal, and the observed sums of some appropriately selected squares are then examined to see whether their ratio is significantly incompatible with this null hypothesis.

The quantity formula_34 has the same distribution in Bayesian statistics, if an uninformative rescaling-invariant Jeffreys prior is taken for the prior probabilities of formula_32 and formula_33. In this context, a scaled &quot;F&quot;-distribution thus gives the posterior probability formula_37, where the observed sums formula_38 and formula_39 are now taken as known.

